abstract: After my diagnosis, I silently held out hope that it had all been a big mistake.
snippet: After my diagnosis, I silently held out hope that it had all been a big mistake.
lead_paragraph: With a slow moving disease like Alzheimer’s, there’s still time for doubt. Perhaps the diagnosis is wrong and the memory holes and struggle for words are just normal aging. Deep in your psyche, there’s still a little spark of hope.

headline.main: Accepting Alzheimer’s, One Lost Memory at a Time
headline.print_headline: Fighting On Against Alzheimer’s

abstract: ‘Menopause-related cognitive impairment happens to women in their 40s and 50s, women in the prime of life who suddenly have the rug pulled out from under them,’ an expert says.
snippet: ‘Menopause-related cognitive impairment happens to women in their 40s and 50s, women in the prime of life who suddenly have the rug pulled out from under them,’ an expert says.
lead_paragraph: Dr. Gayatri Devi’s patient, a 55-year-old former headmistress, had good reason to be distraught. The woman had a yearlong history of progressive memory loss and behavioral problems and was referred to Dr. Devi, a neurologist, with a possible diagnosis of frontotemporal dementia.

abstract: An analysis of inspection records in California, Florida and Texas shows significant numbers of violations related to residents with dementia.
snippet: An analysis of inspection records in California, Florida and Texas shows significant numbers of violations related to residents with dementia.
lead_paragraph: They found Bonnie Walker in a pond behind her assisted living facility in South Carolina. There were puncture wounds on her ear, her temple, her jaw and her cheeks.

headline.main: Dementia Patients Fuel Assisted Living’s Growth. Safety May Be Lagging.
headline.print_headline: Assisted Living Strains to Keep Up With Safety

abstract: Few drugs have been approved for treatment of this dementia, and none works very well. It has become one of the most intractable problems in medicine.
snippet: Few drugs have been approved for treatment of this dementia, and none works very well. It has become one of the most intractable problems in medicine.
lead_paragraph: It’s a rare person in America who doesn’t know of someone with Alzheimer’s disease. The most common type of dementia, it afflicts about 44 million people worldwide, including 5.5 million in the United States.

headline.main: Weekly Health Quiz: Sleep, Stomach Bugs and the Healthiest City

abstract: We had to trick my mother into the memory care center. The doctors called it “therapeutic lying.”
snippet: We had to trick my mother into the memory care center. The doctors called it “therapeutic lying.”
lead_paragraph: Hiding with my older sister in her S.U.V., I’m nauseated. We’re committing a heinous crime. Twenty feet away, I see a paramedic escort my silver-haired mother into the memory care center, a nursing home for patients with dementia and Alzheimer’s.

headline.main: The Dementia Heist

abstract: Stigma often prevents patients from acknowledging an Alzheimer’s diagnosis. A series of high-profile disclosures may help change that.
snippet: Stigma often prevents patients from acknowledging an Alzheimer’s diagnosis. A series of high-profile disclosures may help change that.
lead_paragraph: The spouses arriving for the Wednesday afternoon caregivers’ class at the Penn Memory Center in Philadelphia had something on their minds even before Alison Lynn, the social worker leading the session, could start the conversation.

abstract: Justice O’Connor, 88, was the first woman to serve on the Supreme Court. She wielded immense power and often found ways to bridge divides in a less polarized era.
snippet: Justice O’Connor, 88, was the first woman to serve on the Supreme Court. She wielded immense power and often found ways to bridge divides in a less polarized era.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The first woman to serve on the Supreme Court was just 75, young by its standards, and still sharp and vigorous when she left. But she gave up the job she loved, along with extraordinary power, to guide and comfort her husband, who was struggling with Alzheimer’s disease.

headline.main: Battling Dementia, Sandra Day O’Connor Leaves Public Life With Plea for Bipartisanship
headline.print_headline: Pioneer of Court Calls for Comity In Face of Illness

abstract: Justice O’Connor, 88, said she received the diagnosis “some time ago” and would withdraw from public life. She encouraged the next generation of leaders to promote civic engagement.
snippet: Justice O’Connor, 88, said she received the diagnosis “some time ago” and would withdraw from public life. She encouraged the next generation of leaders to promote civic engagement.
lead_paragraph: Sandra Day O’Connor, the first woman to serve as a justice on the United States Supreme Court and a critical swing vote for much of her tenure, said on Tuesday that she had dementia and had decided to withdraw from public life as the disease advanced.

headline.main: Sandra Day O’Connor, First Woman on Supreme Court, Reveals Dementia Diagnosis

abstract: Up to 5 percent of pregnant women develop pre-eclampsia, which is tied to an increased risk of dementia in later years.
snippet: Up to 5 percent of pregnant women develop pre-eclampsia, which is tied to an increased risk of dementia in later years.
lead_paragraph: Having pre-eclampsia — dangerously high blood pressure during pregnancy — is linked to an increased risk for dementia later in life, according to a new study.

abstract: As the number of Americans with Alzheimer’s disease and other forms of dementia rises, health professionals grapple with how to talk to patients about gun safety at home.
snippet: As the number of Americans with Alzheimer’s disease and other forms of dementia rises, health professionals grapple with how to talk to patients about gun safety at home.
lead_paragraph: Some patients refuse to answer. Many doctors don’t ask. Family members worry about offending a suffering loved one. As the number of Americans with dementia rises, health professionals are grappling with when and how to pose the question: “Do you have guns at home?”

headline.main: Doctors Need to Talk to Families About Guns and Dementia
byline.original: By Melissa Bailey, Kaiser Health News

abstract: As the number of people with dementia rises, those with early stages of the ailment are pursuing fulfilling lives and making plans for future care.
snippet: As the number of people with dementia rises, those with early stages of the ailment are pursuing fulfilling lives and making plans for future care.
lead_paragraph: Laurie Scherrer was a workaholic sales executive when she began forgetting customers and losing her ability to perform simple math calculations. Five years ago, at age 55, she learned she has early-onset Alzheimer’s disease and frontotemporal dementia.

headline.main: Leading an Active Life With a Diagnosis of Dementia

abstract: Men and women who reported feeling sleepy during the day had higher levels of brain plaques.
snippet: Men and women who reported feeling sleepy during the day had higher levels of brain plaques.
lead_paragraph: A new study links daytime sleepiness with the accumulation of the plaques in the brain that are a hallmark of Alzheimer’s disease.

abstract: In the 1960s, Dr. Kao outlined the potential capacity of fiber optic cables for transmitting information, laying the technical groundwork for modern communications.
snippet: In the 1960s, Dr. Kao outlined the potential capacity of fiber optic cables for transmitting information, laying the technical groundwork for modern communications.
lead_paragraph: HONG KONG — Charles Kuen Kao, a Nobel laureate in physics whose research in the 1960s revolutionized the field of fiber optics and helped lay the technical groundwork for the information age, died on Sunday in Hong Kong. He was 84.

abstract: Consumer genetic tests aren’t error-proof.
snippet: Consumer genetic tests aren’t error-proof.
lead_paragraph: In many ways, Matt Fender, a 32-year-old resident of New York City, is the prototypical 23andMe customer: tech-savvy, educated, a bit of a worrier. But he wasn’t worried last December when he clicked a button to dump all the raw data from his 23andMe genetic test into a DNA search engine called Promethease, which sorts through data for gene variants that have received a mention in the medical literature.

headline.main: Smoking May Increase Dementia Risk
headline.print_headline: Mind: Smoking and Dementia Risk

abstract: To find 25,000 participants to enroll in all the approved trials, researchers would have to begin by approaching more than 37 million people with early memory loss.
snippet: To find 25,000 participants to enroll in all the approved trials, researchers would have to begin by approaching more than 37 million people with early memory loss.
lead_paragraph: The task facing Eli Lilly, the giant pharmaceutical company, sounds simple enough: Find 375 people with early Alzheimer’s disease for a bold new clinical trial aiming to slow or stop memory loss.

headline.main: For Scientists Racing to Cure Alzheimer’s, the Math Is Getting Ugly
headline.print_headline: Alzheimer’s Trials Hit a Roadblock

abstract: The drug may be the first to successfully attack both the brain changes and the symptoms of Alzheimer’s. Further research will be needed to know if it’s truly effective.
snippet: The drug may be the first to successfully attack both the brain changes and the symptoms of Alzheimer’s. Further research will be needed to know if it’s truly effective.
lead_paragraph: The long, discouraging quest for a medication that works to treat Alzheimer’s reached a potentially promising milestone on Wednesday. For the first time in a large clinical trial, a drug was able to both reduce the plaques in the brains of patients and slow the progression of dementia.

headline.main: Weekly Health Quiz: Alan Alda, Fat Pets and Chinese Medicine

abstract: The research did not find that viruses cause Alzheimer’s. But it showed that two types of herpes interact with Alzheimer’s-related genes and might drive the disease process.
snippet: The research did not find that viruses cause Alzheimer’s. But it showed that two types of herpes interact with Alzheimer’s-related genes and might drive the disease process.
lead_paragraph: It has long been a controversial theory about Alzheimer’s disease, often dismissed by experts as a sketchy cul-de-sac off the beaten path from mainstream research.

headline.main: The Menopause-Alzheimer’s Connection

abstract: Doctors suggest that hormone replacement therapy can drastically reduce the risk of Alzheimer’s and dementia in women.

abstract: Nick Nolte, Matt Dillon and Emily Mortimer star in this tonally disheveled, occasionally offensive movie.
snippet: Nick Nolte, Matt Dillon and Emily Mortimer star in this tonally disheveled, occasionally offensive movie.
lead_paragraph: The subject of Alzheimer’s gets a tonally disheveled, occasionally offensive treatment in the disastrous “Head Full of Honey,” about a family dealing with (or failing to deal with) the rapidly escalating dementia of the widower Amadeus (Nick Nolte). The warning signs of his condition first appear when, speaking at his wife’s funeral, he goes on a bizarre tangent about pie, praises her breasts, forgets she’s dead and doesn’t seem to have any idea where he is.

abstract: Getting their choices on end-of-life care recorded can help patients feel secure that their wishes will be respected, experts say.
snippet: Getting their choices on end-of-life care recorded can help patients feel secure that their wishes will be respected, experts say.
lead_paragraph: I had hoped that by now most adults in this country would have completed an advance directive for medical care and assigned someone they trusted to represent their wishes if and when they are unable to speak for themselves. Alas, at last count, barely more than one-third have done so, with the rest of Americans leaving it up to the medical profession and ill-prepared family members to decide when and how to provide life-prolonging treatments.

abstract: My mother nearly destroyed me when I was young, but my affection for her increased as the woman she once was diminished.
snippet: My mother nearly destroyed me when I was young, but my affection for her increased as the woman she once was diminished.
lead_paragraph: I am scratching my mother’s head. Her hair is quite thin now and I no longer bother to make an appointment in the nursing home’s “salon” for a cut. It is just another trauma to her, as is taking a shower. When the aides give her a shower I can hear her screaming all the way down the hall, shrieking like a feral cat.

abstract: Following the retired justice’s Alzheimer’s diagnosis, a lawyer writes about getting advice ranging from the role women must play in public life to how to dress.

abstract: Sometimes it seems as if we’re living under a constant barrage of heavy news. But it isn’t all bad out there.
snippet: Sometimes it seems as if we’re living under a constant barrage of heavy news. But it isn’t all bad out there.
lead_paragraph: Sometimes it seems as if we’re living under a constant barrage of heavy news. But it isn’t all bad out there. This feature is meant to send you into the weekend with a smile, or at least a lighter heart. Want to get The Week in Good News by email? Sign up here.

abstract: The Laurie M. Tisch Illumination Fund give grants to organizations who use art to combat mental illness.
snippet: The Laurie M. Tisch Illumination Fund give grants to organizations who use art to combat mental illness.
lead_paragraph: The Laurie M. Tisch Illumination Fund has pledged $10 million to fund arts programs focused on mental health issues in New York City.

abstract: With the increase of Alzheimer’s disease and dementia, estate planners say trusts have become more important.
snippet: With the increase of Alzheimer’s disease and dementia, estate planners say trusts have become more important.
lead_paragraph: Everyone needs a will, but, increasingly, estate planners say people also could benefit from setting up a trust while they are alive. That step would help assure that their assets are distributed more quickly, their bills paid promptly and continuously and personal information about property and other assets be kept out of the public eye.

headline.main: A Father, a Son, a Disease and a Camera

abstract: The mercy of dementia is that Mom is immune to the psychological distress that often accompanies cancer treatment.
snippet: The mercy of dementia is that Mom is immune to the psychological distress that often accompanies cancer treatment.
lead_paragraph: I’m driving my mother to her second week of radiation on a glorious spring day. Pale green leaf-lace froths on the trees, a verdant scribble working its way up the foothills of Mt. Greylock. Spring is an irrepressible fact in New England, not a cliché. And the weather is our favorite subject now that Mom has moderate Alzheimer’s.

abstract: Cheney Orr knew that Alzheimer’s would take his father away. Photography helped him get to know the man.
snippet: Cheney Orr knew that Alzheimer’s would take his father away. Photography helped him get to know the man.
lead_paragraph: Cheney Orr was 21 when his father received a diagnosis of early-onset Alzheimer’s disease in 2011. His father, David, was just 62, and the son felt he had never quite known him as an adult. The camera offered a way to bridge that gap. It was an excuse to visit regularly and a portal through which to understand the disease.

abstract: The documentary charts the career of María Irene Fornés, and follows her as Alzheimer’s steals her memories.
snippet: The documentary charts the career of María Irene Fornés, and follows her as Alzheimer’s steals her memories.
lead_paragraph: Try as it might, sadness still can’t get the best of “The Rest I Make Up,” a lyrical and lovingly made documentary about the playwright María Irene Fornés, which recalls her career and follows her over several bittersweet years as Alzheimer’s steals her memories.

abstract: Electrodes threaded into the brains of epilepsy patients enhanced their recall on word tests by about 15 percent.
snippet: Electrodes threaded into the brains of epilepsy patients enhanced their recall on word tests by about 15 percent.
lead_paragraph: Scientists have developed a brain implant that noticeably boosted memory in its first serious test run, perhaps offering a promising new strategy to treat dementia, traumatic brain injuries and other conditions that damage memory.

headline.main: A Brain Implant Improved Memory, Scientists Report
headline.print_headline: Brain Implant Enhanced Memory, Raising Hope for Treatments, Scientists Say

abstract: Helen Mirren and Donald Sutherland star as a couple, facing illnesses, who take their 1975 Winnebago and set out for Key West, Fla.
snippet: Helen Mirren and Donald Sutherland star as a couple, facing illnesses, who take their 1975 Winnebago and set out for Key West, Fla.
lead_paragraph: “The Leisure Seeker,” the first English-language feature from the Italian director Paolo Virzì, stars Helen Mirren and Donald Sutherland as a couple who skip town in a 1975 Winnebago, heading from Wellesley, Mass., to Florida, without giving notice to anyone, including their grown children. Ella (Ms. Mirren) plans to take John (Mr. Sutherland), an expert on Ernest Hemingway, to the Hemingway Home in Key West.

abstract: Rethink the Christmas classic with Op-Docs, our series of Oscar-nominated short films.
snippet: Rethink the Christmas classic with Op-Docs, our series of Oscar-nominated short films.
lead_paragraph: The story of our modern Santa Claus — magical bearded man, flying reindeer, supersonic sleigh travel — is nothing if not far-fetched. One filmmaker went looking for the source that weirdness, only to fall down a hallucinogenic holiday rabbit hole.
keywords: [{'name': 'subject', 'value': 'Santa Claus', 'rank': 1, 'major': 'N'}, {'name': 'subject', 'value': 'Christmas', 'rank': 2, 'major': 'N'}]

abstract: The couple met in 2013 at RF Binder, a public relations company in New York, where they both worked at the time.
snippet: The couple met in 2013 at RF Binder, a public relations company in New York, where they both worked at the time.
lead_paragraph: Emma Roithmayr and Michael Boonshoft were married Nov. 10 at the Gurney’s Montauk Yacht Club and Resort in Montauk, N.Y. Cantor Irene Failenbogen officiated, with Bill McBride, a former Roman Catholic priest, taking part in an interfaith ceremony.

headline.main: Emma Roithmayr, Michael Boonshoft
headline.print_headline: Emma Roithmayr,  Michael Boonshoft

abstract: The chief executive of 23andMe on paternity testing, A-Rod and Facebook.
snippet: The chief executive of 23andMe on paternity testing, A-Rod and Facebook.
lead_paragraph: Your company, 23andMe, does DNA tests that can tell you what countries your ancestors were from or what genetic diseases you may have or, most important, whether you suffer from “asparagus pee.” But your ultimate ambition is to take data culled from your customers’ DNA and use it to find cures and develop drugs. Why? The health care ecosystem that exists today is a $3-trillion-a-year economy and no one makes money if you stay healthy. There’s very little money that goes into prevention programs, and I think that’s not reflective of what you and I want. What we really care about most is not “How do I manage my Alzheimer’s?” but “How do I never get it in the first place?”

abstract: Bruce had the unenviable task of following the revered Woody Hayes, but he compiled 81 victories over eight seasons before being fired.
snippet: Bruce had the unenviable task of following the revered Woody Hayes, but he compiled 81 victories over eight seasons before being fired.
lead_paragraph: COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) — Earle Bruce, who embraced the unenviable task of following his mentor, the revered Woody Hayes, as Ohio State’s head football coach and then compiled an impressive record of his own beginning in 1979, has died in Columbus. He was 87.

abstract: The company will put on its second citywide festival as well as some classics.
snippet: The company will put on its second citywide festival as well as some classics.
lead_paragraph: Opera Philadelphia has of late prioritized embracing new work and unorthodox programming; last month, New York Times critic Zachary Woolfe wrote that the company “has swiftly become one of the most creative and ambitious in this country.” On Tuesday, the company announced its 2018-19 season, which will include a second annual citywide festival and two world premieres.

abstract: The couple met in 2014 at the Union Club of Philadelphia, and had their first date the next day.
snippet: The couple met in 2014 at the Union Club of Philadelphia, and had their first date the next day.
lead_paragraph: Alexandra Meigs Noll and Stephen Anthony Iacobucci were married June 23 at St. Peter’s Episcopal Church in Philadelphia. The Rev. Dr. Joseph G. Schaller officiated.

abstract: Claudio Cuello grew up in Hamilton Heights. He’s hoping his new job as a security guard can help him return to the neighborhood he loves.
snippet: Claudio Cuello grew up in Hamilton Heights. He’s hoping his new job as a security guard can help him return to the neighborhood he loves.
lead_paragraph: Claudio Cuello’s mother was buried on his birthday.

headline.main: He Lost His Mother and His Neighborhood. A New Career Path Could Lead Him Back.
headline.print_headline: After Years of Loss, a New Career Path Could Help Him Return Home

abstract: Music therapy is becoming more common in nursing homes and hospices, where it has been shown to improve a patient’s quality of life.
snippet: Music therapy is becoming more common in nursing homes and hospices, where it has been shown to improve a patient’s quality of life.
lead_paragraph: At 90, Beverly Herzog is writing songs for the first time.

abstract: “The Waverly Gallery” will feature Michael Cera and Lucas Hedges along with Ms. May, who has not appeared on Broadway in more than 50 years.
snippet: “The Waverly Gallery” will feature Michael Cera and Lucas Hedges along with Ms. May, who has not appeared on Broadway in more than 50 years.
lead_paragraph: Elaine May is returning to Broadway for the first time in more than 50 years to appear in “The Waverly Gallery,” the third Kenneth Lonergan play to reach Broadway since 2014.

abstract: In “Dear Madam President,” the Clinton campaign’s former communications director, Jennifer Palmieri, tells young women how to succeed in politics.

abstract: In “Dear Madam President,” the Clinton campaign’s former communications director, Jennifer Palmieri, tells young women how to succeed in politics.

headline.print_headline: Paperback Row

abstract: Using objects, narratives and technology, museums in Liverpool, England, are rekindling memories and making connections.
snippet: Using objects, narratives and technology, museums in Liverpool, England, are rekindling memories and making connections.
lead_paragraph: An assisted-living facility in Liverpool, England, was confronted with an unusual dilemma in 2013: An elderly resident with severe dementia suddenly became terrified of water and showering — and categorically refused to bathe.

abstract: He became the highest-ranking Catholic official to be convicted of concealing child sexual abuse, and could face two years in prison.
snippet: He became the highest-ranking Catholic official to be convicted of concealing child sexual abuse, and could face two years in prison.
lead_paragraph: MELBOURNE, Australia — An Australian archbishop was convicted on Tuesday of covering up a claim of sexual abuse dating back decades, and now faces a prison sentence of up to two years.

abstract: The impact of air pollution appeared especially stark in older men, a particularly worrying sign for countries with aging populations.

lead_paragraph: HONG KONG — A large study in China suggests a link between air pollution and negative effects on people’s language and math skills.

abstract: Five states already have laws allowing authorities to temporarily remove guns under a judge’s orders. The Florida school shooting has prompted new debate.
snippet: Five states already have laws allowing authorities to temporarily remove guns under a judge’s orders. The Florida school shooting has prompted new debate.
lead_paragraph: In the last two months, law enforcement authorities in California took a gun away from a 38-year-old man who had threatened to kill himself, his wife and their young child if she left him. They removed three weapons from a 23-year-old ex-Marine who, the authorities said, had developed a paranoia that all males wanted to harm him. And they took a handgun from a 39-year-old man whose terrified neighbors reported that he was firing his weapon in the backyard; the man, who said he thought he was aiming for raccoons and rats, was found to be intoxicated, the police said.

headline.main: States Mull ‘Red Flag’ Gun Seizures from People Deemed Dangerous
headline.print_headline: In Some States, Taking Guns From Those Deemed Dangerous

abstract: Americans are increasingly determined to exercise control over their deaths, and some believe suicide ought to be considered a reasonable option.
snippet: Americans are increasingly determined to exercise control over their deaths, and some believe suicide ought to be considered a reasonable option.
lead_paragraph: On a March morning in 1989, Robert Shoots was found dead in his garage in Weir, Kan. He had run a tube from the tailpipe of his beloved old Chrysler to the front seat, where he sat with a bottle of Wild Turkey. He was 80.

headline.main: A Debate Over ‘Rational Suicide’
headline.print_headline: You’re Not Ill, Just Old. Is Suicide a Rational Choice?

abstract: With questions swirling around Mr. Trump’s mental health, his coming physical may yield few clues about whether he is, as his former doctor claimed during his candidacy, the “healthiest individual” to hold the office.
snippet: With questions swirling around Mr. Trump’s mental health, his coming physical may yield few clues about whether he is, as his former doctor claimed during his candidacy, the “healthiest individual” to hold the office.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump is a commander in chief who fuels himself with a steady stream of Diet Cokes, scoops of vanilla ice cream and slabs of red meat. He gets as little as five hours of sleep a night. He is not known to exercise more than the brief strolls beyond his cart on the golf course.

abstract: This week’s episode was essentially one long “what if” — and left a lot of unanswered questions heading into the finale.
snippet: This week’s episode was essentially one long “what if” — and left a lot of unanswered questions heading into the finale.
lead_paragraph: The town of Castle Rock makes its first prominent appearance in “The Dead Zone,” the 1979 Stephen King novel in which a local schoolteacher named Johnny Smith uses his psychic abilities to help Sheriff George Bannerman track a serial killer. Smith’s powers are triggered by touch: He brushes against someone’s hand and sees their future unspooling in his mind, like a movie. But his predictions aren’t fixed. If he takes action, he can alter the timeline.

abstract: In his new book, the neuroscientist Eric Kandel explores the science of unusual brains, locating many of his answers in genetics.

abstract: From the sidesplitting to the heartbreaking, the mysterious to the political, this must-listen list has something for everyone in your car.
snippet: From the sidesplitting to the heartbreaking, the mysterious to the political, this must-listen list has something for everyone in your car.
lead_paragraph: We’re barreling toward summer, with long drives and leisure hours ahead. It’s the time of year when friends who know I’m an audiobook nut ask for suggestions. Podcasts offer more flash and dazzle, but I still love the long arc of books “on tape” as an antidote to the shattered attention span of a Twitter-fied society. Recommendations can be tricky (unless the friend hasn’t heard my recent favorite, Amor Towles’s wonderful novel “A Gentleman in Moscow,” read with wry sadness and perfect comic timing by Nicholas Guy Smith. You’re welcome). What follows is an eclectic list of audiobooks that might provide ideas for your next summer drive.

headline.main: Mars, Pakistan, Facebook: Your Thursday Briefing

abstract: Lawmakers are pushing for billions in new funding for biomedical research, but sparring over health insurance and almost everything else related to the Affordable Care Act.
snippet: Lawmakers are pushing for billions in new funding for biomedical research, but sparring over health insurance and almost everything else related to the Affordable Care Act.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — They cannot agree on subsidies for low-income people under the Affordable Care Act or even how to extend funding for the broadly popular Children’s Health Insurance Program — two issues requiring urgent attention as Congress returns to work.

abstract: It’s not just what makes males into males. The sex chromosome also influences health in hidden ways, some experts believe, and may even explain why men have shorter life spans.
snippet: It’s not just what makes males into males. The sex chromosome also influences health in hidden ways, some experts believe, and may even explain why men have shorter life spans.
lead_paragraph: In advance of Father’s Day, let’s take a moment to sort out the differences and similarities between “Dad jeans” and “Dad genes.”

abstract: Articles about the test, known as the Montreal Cognitive Assessment, or MoCA, listed some of its questions, potentially influencing future patients.
snippet: Articles about the test, known as the Montreal Cognitive Assessment, or MoCA, listed some of its questions, potentially influencing future patients.
lead_paragraph: Six months after a White House physician told reporters that President Trump had aced a well-regarded test of cognitive impairment, a group of doctors is warning that the exam may have been compromised by the resulting news coverage, which revealed some of its questions.

abstract: In the 1980s, Ms. Cunningham and Bill Agee were the central figures in one of the most famous sex scandals in corporate America. Four decades later, she sees it as one of the first #MeToo moments.
snippet: In the 1980s, Ms. Cunningham and Bill Agee were the central figures in one of the most famous sex scandals in corporate America. Four decades later, she sees it as one of the first #MeToo moments.
lead_paragraph: In the tightknit community of St. Helena, Calif., Mary Cunningham Agee is known as the Tomato Lady. She grows the best heirlooms, giving them out, along with basil, cabbage and cauliflower, to her Napa Valley neighbors. Vineyards line both sides of her 4,000-square-foot farmhouse, the one with the soft golden-white hue and the shutters with heart-shaped cutouts. Ms. Cunningham Agee tends to the grapes to produce 25 cases of pinot noir each season.

headline.main: Before There Was #MeToo, There Was Mary Cunningham
headline.print_headline: A Woman of Her Time

abstract: Philip Edward Wilson, the archbishop of Adelaide, Australia, was the second prelate whose resignation Pope Francis accepted in three days.
snippet: Philip Edward Wilson, the archbishop of Adelaide, Australia, was the second prelate whose resignation Pope Francis accepted in three days.
lead_paragraph: ROME — For the second time in three days, Pope Francis on Monday accepted the resignation of a powerful prelate — this time, an Australian archbishop — in a sexual abuse scandal, as the pontiff tries to send the message that high officials no longer enjoy near-immunity from consequences within the church when it comes to sexual misconduct.

abstract: A reporter finds parallels between his own story and the powerful and painful tales of those returning to Puerto Rico after Hurricane Maria.
snippet: A reporter finds parallels between his own story and the powerful and painful tales of those returning to Puerto Rico after Hurricane Maria.
lead_paragraph: Much has been reported on the hundreds of thousands of people who fled Puerto Rico after Hurricane Maria’s powerful winds ravaged the island. But barely anything had been written about what it is like for Puerto Ricans who return to the island after months in exile — the basis for my recent story about a couple’s return home.

headline.main: In Puerto Rico, Following Stories That Hit Close to Home
headline.print_headline: Puerto Ricans Seeking a Place to Rest

abstract: He made Bain & Company, in Boston, a fierce competitor to some of the country’s leading firms. Mitt Romney was one of his most significant hires.
snippet: He made Bain & Company, in Boston, a fierce competitor to some of the country’s leading firms. Mitt Romney was one of his most significant hires.
lead_paragraph: William W. Bain Jr., who founded the business consulting firm Bain & Company and was an early mentor to Mitt Romney, died on Tuesday at his home in Naples, Fla. He was 80.

abstract: Mr. Kasell started off as an anchorman and later in his career became an absurdist comedian on the popular quiz show “Wait Wait ... Don’t Tell Me.”
snippet: Mr. Kasell started off as an anchorman and later in his career became an absurdist comedian on the popular quiz show “Wait Wait ... Don’t Tell Me.”
lead_paragraph: Carl Kasell, an NPR newscaster who, late in his career, cast off his anchorman gravitas once a week and for years became an absurdist comedian on the popular satirical quiz show “Wait Wait … Don’t Tell Me!,” died on Tuesday in Potomac, Md. He was 84.

abstract: As a former military psychiatrist, I worry that the president would fail the military’s mental health standards.
snippet: As a former military psychiatrist, I worry that the president would fail the military’s mental health standards.
lead_paragraph: As a psychiatrist for the United States Air Force, one of my responsibilities was evaluating the mental stability of airmen who handled nuclear weapons, using the standards laid out in what is called the Nuclear Personnel Reliability Program. There is no need to justify why our military would take every precaution necessary to ensure that the men and women in uniform handling nuclear weapons were fit to do so, whether they were in charge of a missile silo or loading nuclear bombs onto aircraft — or giving the orders to them, on up the chain of command. Strangely, the commander-in-chief, the one who would decide when and how to use those weapons, is the only individual in the chain who is not subject to the ongoing certification under the program.

abstract: The trick is not to increase life span, scientists say, but to lengthen “health span.”
snippet: The trick is not to increase life span, scientists say, but to lengthen “health span.”
lead_paragraph: The most common risk factor for serious disease is old age. Heart disease, cancer, stroke, neurological conditions, diabetes — all increase radically with advancing years. And the older a person is, the more likely he or she is to have multiple chronic illnesses.

abstract: Given what Trump is doing to our government, it’s a good thing he’s a very stable genius.
snippet: Given what Trump is doing to our government, it’s a good thing he’s a very stable genius.
lead_paragraph: Like millions of people around the world, I was reassured to learn that Donald Trump is a “Very Stable Genius.” You see, if he weren’t — if he were instead an erratic, vindictive, uninformed, lazy, would-be tyrant — we might be in real trouble.

abstract: “Don’t you have better things to do than watch me vacuum apartments?” wondered a cleaning woman I spent some time tagging along with. I didn’t.

abstract: “I never understand at an auction when something goes for $100 million and everybody starts clapping. I always think, Did they also cure cancer?”
snippet: “I never understand at an auction when something goes for $100 million and everybody starts clapping. I always think, Did they also cure cancer?”
lead_paragraph: Laurie M. Tisch’s apartment on the Upper East Side of Manhattan has spectacular views of Central Park. Reflecting her passions and role as a trustee at the Whitney Museum of American Art, it is filled with classic paintings by the country’s renowned modernists, including Edward Hopper, Milton Avery, Jacob Lawrence, Thomas Hart Benton and Georgia O’Keeffe (with a radiant new acquisition of her “Blue Morning Glories”).

abstract: Months after Hurricane Maria, the island is struggling to regain its balance. The flora tell a melancholy story.
snippet: Months after Hurricane Maria, the island is struggling to regain its balance. The flora tell a melancholy story.
lead_paragraph: Last November, with Puerto Rico thrown into chaos after Hurricane Maria, I was frantically trying to reach a funeral home in San Juan. My dear cousin Alma Otero-Pérez, a free-spirited poet who was my mentor and model growing up on the island, had died overnight at her home for patients with Alzheimer’s. I loved her and the loss pained me, but as her guardian, I needed to focus on medical and legal paperwork and making the necessary funeral arrangements from New York.

abstract: Known for his confrontational style, Mr. Luken was a major force in Cincinnati for more than 30 years, as a prosecutor, the mayor and a member of Congress.
snippet: Known for his confrontational style, Mr. Luken was a major force in Cincinnati for more than 30 years, as a prosecutor, the mayor and a member of Congress.
lead_paragraph: Thomas Luken, a political force in Ohio for more than 30 years as a federal prosecutor, a member of Congress and the mayor of Cincinnati, died on Wednesday in Cincinnati. He was 92.

headline.main: Thomas Luken, Veteran Ohio Democrat, Is Dead at 92
headline.print_headline: Thomas Luken Dies at 92;  A Stalwart of Ohio Politics

abstract: Eric Sirota and Cara London had nothing in common when they met 25 years ago. They have not grown more alike, only more tolerant of their differences.
snippet: Eric Sirota and Cara London had nothing in common when they met 25 years ago. They have not grown more alike, only more tolerant of their differences.
lead_paragraph: In his 20s and early 30s, Eric Sirota was a single physicist who lived alone and often felt like Victor, the solitary scientist in Mary Shelley’s novel “Frankenstein.” Mr. Sirota, who also composes musicals, even began working on one inspired by the Frankenstein story. “The message is that everyone deserves a chance at love,” he said of his interpretation. “You have to go find it and nurture it but it’s something people are entitled to, and it makes them better people.”

abstract: The Emmy-winning actor, who won accolades in London for playing a deranged anchorman in “Network,” isn’t so sure his character is wrongheaded.
snippet: The Emmy-winning actor, who won accolades in London for playing a deranged anchorman in “Network,” isn’t so sure his character is wrongheaded.
lead_paragraph: As Howard Beale, the mad prophet of the airwaves in Broadway’s “Network,” Bryan Cranston spends eight shows a week inveighing against “the depression, and the inflation and the defense budget and crime in the street … and the Russians,” urging his viewers to get as livid as he is and threatening to blow his brains out on live TV. Even when measured against Mr. Cranston’s previous work on “Breaking Bad” and “All the Way,” that’s a lot of rage that the actor has had to channel on a regular basis (dating back to the play’s original run last year at London’s National Theater).

abstract: Ms. Maslen created Bob Books, simple stories simply illustrated, and thereby helped teach countless youngsters to read.
snippet: Ms. Maslen created Bob Books, simple stories simply illustrated, and thereby helped teach countless youngsters to read.
lead_paragraph: If you’re a teacher, sometimes the best classroom materials are the ones you improvise yourself.

headline.main: Bobby Lynn Maslen, Who Found Young Readers’ Wavelength, Dies at 87
headline.print_headline: Bobby Lynn Maslen, Author, Dies at 87

abstract: She starred in the Broadway hit “Where’s Charley?” in 1948 and went on to TV fame on “The Tony Randall Show” and “The Days and Nights of Molly Dodd.”
snippet: She starred in the Broadway hit “Where’s Charley?” in 1948 and went on to TV fame on “The Tony Randall Show” and “The Days and Nights of Molly Dodd.”
lead_paragraph: Allyn Ann McLerie, who drew attention on Broadway when she was 21 in “Where’s Charley?,” then became a familiar screen presence through numerous movie and television roles, died on May 21 in North Bend, Wash. She was 91.

abstract: Aerobic fitness can halve the likelihood of developing heart disease, no matter how worrisome your genetic profile.
snippet: Aerobic fitness can halve the likelihood of developing heart disease, no matter how worrisome your genetic profile.
lead_paragraph: Does heart disease run in your family? You could most likely slash your risk of developing or dying from heart disease if you are physically fit. Being strong helps too.

headline.main: To Slash Your Risk of Heart Disease, Keep Moving
headline.print_headline: Want to Slash Heart Risks? Move It

abstract: Federal investigators say they have found huge gaps in the regulation of assisted living facilities that take care of Medicaid beneficiaries.
snippet: Federal investigators say they have found huge gaps in the regulation of assisted living facilities that take care of Medicaid beneficiaries.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Federal investigators say they have found huge gaps in the regulation of assisted living facilities, a shortfall that they say has potentially jeopardized the care of hundreds of thousands of people served by the booming industry.

abstract: These voters are leaving the Republican Party and we need to win them back.
snippet: These voters are leaving the Republican Party and we need to win them back.
lead_paragraph: An election provides a certain definitiveness for political candidates, win or lose. I know from experience, having lived through both the ups and the downs. For political parties, elections also provide a chance to reflect, learn and move forward with the business of attracting more voters next time. Or at least they should.

headline.main: Republicans Need a Suburban Agenda

abstract: As chairman of the Federal Trade Commission in the Clinton administration, he looked beyond traditional views of antitrust enforcement.
snippet: As chairman of the Federal Trade Commission in the Clinton administration, he looked beyond traditional views of antitrust enforcement.
lead_paragraph: Robert Pitofsky, who as chairman of the Federal Trade Commission in the Clinton administration advocated stricter enforcement of competition and greater protection for consumers, died on Oct. 6 at his home in Chevy Chase, Md. He was 88.

headline.main: Robert Pitofsky, Champion of Consumer Protection, Dies at 88
headline.print_headline: Robert Pitofsky, Antitrust Advocate, Is Dead at 88

abstract: Her welded-metal sculptures were known for their grace and sense of motion.
snippet: Her welded-metal sculptures were known for their grace and sense of motion.
lead_paragraph: Barbara Lekberg, a sculptor who infused her welded-metal works with motion and grace in a career that spanned more than 60 years, died on Feb. 14 at a nursing home in the Bronx. She was 92.

abstract: Without proper neuropsychological testing of the president, we can’t know if he has a mental disorder or is a narcissistic bully.
snippet: Without proper neuropsychological testing of the president, we can’t know if he has a mental disorder or is a narcissistic bully.
lead_paragraph: As a past president of the American Psychiatric Association, I feel strongly that my fellow psychiatrists, and any psychologists or therapists, should stop speculating publicly about President Trump’s mental fitness and stop trying to diagnose possible mental conditions based on their armchair observations.

abstract: Revivals, transfers and new plays that look to the past make for an unusually reflective October theater scene.
snippet: Revivals, transfers and new plays that look to the past make for an unusually reflective October theater scene.
lead_paragraph: Revivals sometimes get a bad name for banking on audience complacency. But in the best cases they offer a chance to find potently timely surprises in works that seemed to live only in one era. (Without revivals, you can’t have classics.) And new plays that revisit the recent past can offer a similar shift in perspective. This month, a few of each stand out.

abstract: Born in Lithuania, raised in South Africa and working in Britain, he made large strides in understanding the structure of proteins, DNA and more.
snippet: Born in Lithuania, raised in South Africa and working in Britain, he made large strides in understanding the structure of proteins, DNA and more.
lead_paragraph: Aaron Klug, who won the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1982 for devising ways to create three-dimensional images of biological molecules like proteins and DNA, died on Nov. 20. He was 92.

abstract: After halting a discredited alcohol study, officials will enforce new policies to ensure that private support does not compromise scientific integrity.
snippet: After halting a discredited alcohol study, officials will enforce new policies to ensure that private support does not compromise scientific integrity.
lead_paragraph: Six months after halting a study of moderate drinking that was underwritten by donations from the alcohol industry, the National Institutes of Health outlined a series of steps to prevent similar conflicts of interest and to safeguard the integrity of its research and its reputation.

headline.print_headline: U.S. Institutes of Health Take Steps to Guard Objectivity of Research

abstract: A show set inside a smartphone is silly yet surprisingly resonant with contemporary politics.
snippet: A show set inside a smartphone is silly yet surprisingly resonant with contemporary politics.
lead_paragraph: “Emojiland” takes place inside a smartphone, in a digital mini-world peopled with emojis, and its hero looks about the way you’d think: like an undiluted dweeb — though, since this is a pop musical, the chartreuse frames on his glasses are kind of fabulous.

abstract: After being passed over at Xerox, he became one of the few African-American chief executives of a Fortune 500 company when he took control of Avis.
snippet: After being passed over at Xerox, he became one of the few African-American chief executives of a Fortune 500 company when he took control of Avis.
lead_paragraph: Barry Rand, who in 1999 became one of the few African-American chief executives of a Fortune 500 company when he took control of Avis, the rental car company, after being passed over for the top job at Xerox, died on Nov. 7 in an assisted living facility in Norwalk, Conn. He was 74.

abstract: He was among the founders of East West Players, a theater troupe that sought better roles for Asian-American actors and more representative stories.
snippet: He was among the founders of East West Players, a theater troupe that sought better roles for Asian-American actors and more representative stories.
lead_paragraph: In 1965, Pat Li of East West Players explained why the company, which she and eight others had started that year in Los Angeles to promote substantive roles for Asian-American actors, was needed.

headline.main: Soon-Tek Oh, Actor Who Chafed at Asian Stereotypes, Dies at 85
headline.print_headline: Soon-Tek Oh, Actor Who Endeavored To Broaden Roles for Asians, Dies at 85

abstract: It seems sensible to encourage “personal responsibility,” and yet policies that invoke the phrase can make health problems worse.
snippet: It seems sensible to encourage “personal responsibility,” and yet policies that invoke the phrase can make health problems worse.
lead_paragraph: On my pediatrics rotation in medical school, several residents told me they worked with children in part because they sometimes found themselves judging adults: Did they do drugs? Were they fat? Why did they drink so much?

headline.main: What Scientific Mysteries Do You Want Solved?

abstract: Pharmaceutical ads have long featured healthy-looking actors or celebrity pitches. Now there’s an increased desire to use people who have taken the medications.
snippet: Pharmaceutical ads have long featured healthy-looking actors or celebrity pitches. Now there’s an increased desire to use people who have taken the medications.
lead_paragraph: Several years ago, a casting director working on a commercial for the NovoLog FlexPen, a dial-a-dose insulin injector from Novo Nordisk, called a friend and urged her to try out.

abstract: Choral practice can help participants take fewer medications, experience less depression and make fewer hospital visits.

lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — When retirees settle into life after work, an inevitable question arises: What kinds of commitments can still be made to friends, neighbors and organizations?

abstract: Robots may be better than nothing, but they still won’t be enough.
snippet: Robots may be better than nothing, but they still won’t be enough.
lead_paragraph: Years ago I spoke with a 16-year-old girl who was considering the idea of having a computer companion in the future, and she described the upside to me. It’s not that the robot she’d imagined, a vastly more sophisticated Siri, was so inspiring. It’s that she’d already found people to be so disappointing. And now, for the first time, she explained me, people have options. Back then I thought her comments seemed prescient. Now I find them timely.

headline.main: There Will Never Be an Age of Artificial Intimacy

abstract: A study of Stephen Paddock’s brain revealed an abnormally high number of structures associated with age, but no evidence of neurological disorders.
snippet: A study of Stephen Paddock’s brain revealed an abnormally high number of structures associated with age, but no evidence of neurological disorders.
lead_paragraph: Stephen Paddock, the 64-year-old gunman who killed 58 concertgoers in Las Vegas last October in the worst mass shooting in modern American history, had not had a stroke, brain tumor or a number of other neurological disorders that might have helped explain his actions, a recent autopsy and examination of the remains of his brain showed.

abstract: He oversaw the expansion of U.S. News & World Report’s annual college rankings, a boon to high school seniors but also a target of criticism.
snippet: He oversaw the expansion of U.S. News & World Report’s annual college rankings, a boon to high school seniors but also a target of criticism.
lead_paragraph: Mel Elfin, a longtime Washington bureau chief for Newsweek who moved to the rival U.S. News & World Report in 1986 and helped build its college rankings feature into a major educational franchise, died on Saturday in Washington. He was 89.

headline.main: Summer Reading Contest, Week 7: What Interested You Most in The Times This Week?

abstract: There’s a sense of wistfulness among aging Cuban exiles in Miami: Cuba will no longer be led by a Castro. But they don’t expect real change anytime soon.
snippet: There’s a sense of wistfulness among aging Cuban exiles in Miami: Cuba will no longer be led by a Castro. But they don’t expect real change anytime soon.
lead_paragraph: MIAMI — The old Cuban fighters gathered under a cloudless South Florida sky and belted out two national anthems — one for their country a few hundred miles south, the one that gave them life, the other for this country, the one that will probably see their death.

abstract: If Utah legalizes medical marijuana on Tuesday, it could signal that the church is no longer all-powerful in state politics.
snippet: If Utah legalizes medical marijuana on Tuesday, it could signal that the church is no longer all-powerful in state politics.
lead_paragraph: SALT LAKE CITY — In September, a billboard appeared near downtown here urging voters to support Proposition 2, an initiative to legalize medical marijuana that is on the ballot Tuesday. Quoting from Mormon Church scripture and its “word of wisdom” about food and drink, the billboard read, “All Wholesome Herbs God Has Ordained for the Use of Man.” In other words, you can use pot for your medical ills and still be a good Mormon.

abstract: Opera Philadelphia’s O18 festival, which continues through Sunday, has more success with standard offerings than out-of-the-box events.
snippet: Opera Philadelphia’s O18 festival, which continues through Sunday, has more success with standard offerings than out-of-the-box events.
lead_paragraph: PHILADELPHIA — “None of this old tired stuff done in the same way,” a character said in a show here last weekend, though he used saltier language.

abstract: Beyond the human suffering, diet-related diseases impose massive economic costs.

headline.print_headline: The Toll of America’s Obesity
byline.original: By David S. Ludwig and Kenneth S. Rogoff

abstract: He led Brigham Young to a championship in 1951, raising the university’s profile before turning pro. He was also part of a formidable sports family.
snippet: He led Brigham Young to a championship in 1951, raising the university’s profile before turning pro. He was also part of a formidable sports family.
lead_paragraph: Mel Hutchins, the All-American center who helped elevate Brigham Young University to the top ranks of college basketball in 1951 and became an N.B.A. All-Star and a senior member of a remarkable sports family, died on Wednesday in Encinitas, Calif. He was 90.

headline.print_headline: Mel Hutchins, B.Y.U. All-American  And N.B.A. All-Star, Is Dead at 90

abstract: With her husband, Newton, she formed an artistic team that examined ecosystems, global warming and related subjects in innovative ways.
snippet: With her husband, Newton, she formed an artistic team that examined ecosystems, global warming and related subjects in innovative ways.
lead_paragraph: Helen Mayer Harrison, half of the husband-and-wife team known as the Harrisons, pioneers in the eco-art movement whose works blended elements of art, biology, environmentalism and more, died on March 24 in Santa Cruz, Calif. She was 90.

headline.main: Finding Purpose for a Good Life. But Also a Healthy One.

abstract: A scholar and a pastor, Rabbi Posner served for 40 years at Temple Emanu-El in Manhattan, giving succor to the sick and reaching out to other faiths.
snippet: A scholar and a pastor, Rabbi Posner served for 40 years at Temple Emanu-El in Manhattan, giving succor to the sick and reaching out to other faiths.
lead_paragraph: At Temple Emanu-El on Fifth Avenue in Manhattan, a flagship Jewish congregation in the Reform tradition since the 19th century, services have traditionally been a formal and grand affair, with “thee” and “thou” in the prayer book, an ethereal choir and a towering sanctuary glowing with stained glass.

abstract: A well-traveled print and broadcast reporter, he covered the biggest stories of his day, including the Vietnam War and the civil rights movement.
snippet: A well-traveled print and broadcast reporter, he covered the biggest stories of his day, including the Vietnam War and the civil rights movement.
lead_paragraph: Murray Fromson, a well-traveled print and broadcast reporter who helped found the Reporters Committee for Freedom of the Press at a time when journalists faced hostility during President Richard M. Nixon’s administration, died on Saturday in Los Angeles. He was 88.

headline.print_headline: Murray Fromson, 88, Press Freedom Champion

abstract: Four days after the Camp Fire blaze ripped through the small town of Paradise, Calif., more than 200 residents are still missing, the sheriff’s office said.
snippet: Four days after the Camp Fire blaze ripped through the small town of Paradise, Calif., more than 200 residents are still missing, the sheriff’s office said.

headline.print_headline: Close-Knit Retirees Fear for Those Not Heard From

abstract: At Vassar and then at Yale’s Medical School, Dr. Hamburg blazed trails for black women. Then came a distinguished career in child development.
snippet: At Vassar and then at Yale’s Medical School, Dr. Hamburg blazed trails for black women. Then came a distinguished career in child development.
lead_paragraph: Beatrix Hamburg, who after breaking racial barriers at two major colleges became an important researcher in child development and psychology, working on subjects like school violence and peer counseling for students, died on April 15 in Washington. She was 94.

abstract: Some very wealthy people are serious about outsmarting mortality.
snippet: Some very wealthy people are serious about outsmarting mortality.
lead_paragraph: Would you like to live forever? Some billionaires, already invincible in every other way, have decided that they also deserve not to die. Today several biotech companies, fueled by Silicon Valley fortunes, are devoted to “life extension” — or as some put it, to solving “the problem of death.”

abstract: Fish clearly has health benefits, but fish oil supplements may not carry the same ones.
snippet: Fish clearly has health benefits, but fish oil supplements may not carry the same ones.
lead_paragraph: About 15 years ago, when my cholesterol level began an inexplicable climb, I tried a slew of suggested dietary remedies that included eating more fish, along with a daily supplement of fish oil, which research at the time suggested would help prevent heart attacks and strokes.

abstract: “Works of art should not be seen in isolation,” said Mr. Stern, who joined with his father-in-law to create a vast outdoor sculpture garden.
snippet: “Works of art should not be seen in isolation,” said Mr. Stern, who joined with his father-in-law to create a vast outdoor sculpture garden.
lead_paragraph: H. Peter Stern, who co-founded Storm King Art Center in Mountainville, N.Y., and developed it into a prestigious outdoor sculpture museum with modern and contemporary works arrayed over a vast pastoral landscape, died on Monday at his home in Manhattan. He was 90.

abstract: Trump’s nomination for Veterans Affairs Secretary fits a pattern of cronyism.
snippet: Trump’s nomination for Veterans Affairs Secretary fits a pattern of cronyism.
lead_paragraph: In announcing Dr. Ronny Jackson, the White House physician, as his choice to be the new secretary for veterans affairs, President Trump has taken his latest misstep in what has been the worst presidential personnel process in modern history.

abstract: Her dance school in New Haven influenced many, and her outspokenness as a black lesbian feminist influenced many more.
snippet: Her dance school in New Haven influenced many, and her outspokenness as a black lesbian feminist influenced many more.
lead_paragraph: Angela Bowen, who in a varied and influential life was a dancer, a dance teacher, a scholar and a passionate voice on lesbian, black and feminist issues, died on July 12 in Long Beach, Calif. She was 82.

abstract: Nick Drnaso’s “Sabrina” and Michael Kupperman’s “All the Answers” both center on characters who set off a story by disappearing.
snippet: Nick Drnaso’s “Sabrina” and Michael Kupperman’s “All the Answers” both center on characters who set off a story by disappearing.
lead_paragraph: Six pages into SABRINA (Drawn and Quarterly, $27.95), Nick Drnaso’s new graphic novel, the title character’s sister reads out a clue from the crossword puzzle she’s working on. “Twelve letters,” she says. “We killed the Clutter family.” Sabrina knows the answer: “Dick and Perry” — the killers made famous by Truman Capote’s “In Cold Blood.” On first read, it’s just an example of the conversational vérité that Drnaso excels at, the brief reunion between the two adult siblings at their mom’s house in Chicago. Four pages later, Sabrina heads out the door, the last time we see her alive.

abstract: John Leland, Times reporter and author, is discussing his new book, “Happiness Is a Choice You Make,” based on his 2015 series for the Times that explored the lives New Yorkers 85 and over.

abstract: A growing number of museums bring stimulation and solace to dementia patients through regular tours.
snippet: A growing number of museums bring stimulation and solace to dementia patients through regular tours.
lead_paragraph: DUISBURG, Germany — As a private tour of the museum’s contemporary art exhibition began, there was little to differentiate the elderly visitors from any others. Gazing up at a copper sculpture of a large tree, a former housewife, murmured “That’s nice!”

abstract: Paul Bloodgood’s collage-poems; Lutz Bacher’s examination of Mao Zedong’s cult of personality; and a Jack Smith retrospective at Artists Space.

abstract: Since 1999, suicide rates have risen in almost every state and by 25 percent nationwide. Health officials are scrambling for solutions.
snippet: Since 1999, suicide rates have risen in almost every state and by 25 percent nationwide. Health officials are scrambling for solutions.
lead_paragraph: Suicide rates rose steadily in nearly every state from 1999 to 2016, increasing 25 percent nationally, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention reported on Thursday. In 2016, there were more than twice as many suicides as homicides.

headline.main: Defying Prevention Efforts, Suicide Rates Are Climbing Across the Nation
headline.print_headline: Suicide Rate Climbed 25 Percent Even as Prevention Efforts Grew

abstract: Adults also need to get vaccinated to provide herd immunity for others, especially babies and older people.
snippet: Adults also need to get vaccinated to provide herd immunity for others, especially babies and older people.
lead_paragraph: One of the biggest problems in trying to convince people that they need to immunize against things like the flu is that they don’t really feel the pressure. After all, for most people, the flu shot is an inconvenience, and they’re unlikely to get the flu in a given year. So why bother? Quite a few readers expressed this view after my article “Why It’s Still Worth Getting a Flu Shot” on Thursday, including this one.

headline.main: Trade, World Cup, Jacinda Ardern: Your Friday Briefing

abstract: An exhibition at the Belvedere Museum in Vienna explores shifting attitudes toward beauty and age as populations grow older.
snippet: An exhibition at the Belvedere Museum in Vienna explores shifting attitudes toward beauty and age as populations grow older.
lead_paragraph: VIENNA — The day after I arrived in this grand city, the ostentatious capital of an empire that vanished 100 years ago, a taxi emblazoned with an ad for an Austrian brand of mineral water drove past me. Its slogan, rendered in now customary hashtag form, was #jungbleiben — or #stayyoung — and in TV commercials for the campaign, Keira Knightley and Sienna Miller swig straight from the bottles, and Agyness Deyn shouts in passable German, “If you want to stay young, you’d better get started early.” Spend more, consume more, drink up — but never, ever get old.

headline.main: ‘Aging Pride’ Challenges the Cult of Youth
headline.print_headline: Challenging the Cult of Youth

abstract: Medicare health plans will be able to combine medical and social services under a new law that had support from both parties in Congress and the Trump administration.
snippet: Medicare health plans will be able to combine medical and social services under a new law that had support from both parties in Congress and the Trump administration.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Congress and the Trump administration are revamping Medicare to provide extra benefits to people with multiple chronic illnesses, a significant departure from the program’s traditional focus that aims to create a new model of care for millions of older Americans.

abstract: Schooled in Paris, she was a strong-willed teacher of traditional French cuisine for modern tastes and an influential chef and restaurateur.
snippet: Schooled in Paris, she was a strong-willed teacher of traditional French cuisine for modern tastes and an influential chef and restaurateur.
lead_paragraph: Madeleine Kamman was not yet a renowned French chef and teacher in the spring of 1968 when she read a newspaper recipe for snails provençale on toast.

headline.main: Madeleine Kamman, 87, Who Gave Americans a Taste of France, Dies
headline.print_headline: Madeleine Kamman, Chef Who Gave Americans a Taste of France, Dies at 87

abstract: The Irish have now beaten UConn, the juggernaut of women’s basketball, four times in the national semifinals since 2001.
snippet: The Irish have now beaten UConn, the juggernaut of women’s basketball, four times in the national semifinals since 2001.
lead_paragraph: COLUMBUS, Ohio — Connecticut has never lost in the championship game at the women’s Final Four, unblemished in collecting 11 N.C.A.A. basketball titles. But the Huskies can be vulnerable in the taut, desperate preamble of the semifinals. No one understands this more acutely than Notre Dame.

abstract: One reason for the evictions, legal advocates say, is that the residents’ better-paying Medicare coverage is ending and will be replaced by Medicaid.
snippet: One reason for the evictions, legal advocates say, is that the residents’ better-paying Medicare coverage is ending and will be replaced by Medicaid.
lead_paragraph: Six weeks after Deborah Zwaschka-Blansfield had the lower half of her left leg amputated, she received some news from the nursing home where she was recovering: Her insurance would no longer pay, and it was time to move on.

abstract: Multigenerational and shared housing arrangements are on the rise, reversing a decades-long trend.
snippet: Multigenerational and shared housing arrangements are on the rise, reversing a decades-long trend.
lead_paragraph: On a Sunday evening a few weeks back, Shobana Ram was loading the dishwasher in her kitchen in Queens when her 85-year-old father-in-law rose from the dinner table, carrying his cane in one hand and an empty plate in the other.

headline.print_headline: When the Parents Are Back, This Time for Good

abstract: Mr. Gold was a behind-the-scenes superstar whose artwork offered moviegoers tantalizing glimpses of the raptures awaiting in the cinema darkness.
snippet: Mr. Gold was a behind-the-scenes superstar whose artwork offered moviegoers tantalizing glimpses of the raptures awaiting in the cinema darkness.
lead_paragraph: Bill Gold, who created posters for “Casablanca,” “A Streetcar Named Desire,” “Alien,” “Mystic River” and hundreds of other films with an artistry that captured the intrigue, romance and drama of Hollywood for nearly 70 years, died on Sunday in Greenwich, Conn. He was 97.

abstract: At West Bromwich Albion, a community health program brings together fans battling memory issues and helps them remember what they’ve seen, and who they are.
snippet: At West Bromwich Albion, a community health program brings together fans battling memory issues and helps them remember what they’ve seen, and who they are.
lead_paragraph: WEST BROMWICH, England — Steve Griffiths first noticed something was wrong about four years ago. The clues were only little things — putting something down and not being able to remember where, forgetting longstanding appointments — but they were enough to make him worry.

abstract: Henry Alford’s “And Then We Danced” and Laura Jacobs’s “Celestial Bodies” explore the cultural and personal resonances of the art of movement.
snippet: Henry Alford’s “And Then We Danced” and Laura Jacobs’s “Celestial Bodies” explore the cultural and personal resonances of the art of movement.
lead_paragraph: AND THEN WE DANCED A Voyage Into the Groove By Henry Alford 256 pp. Simon & Schuster. $26.

abstract: Ms. Fornés won acclaim and awards for her experimental works. But her fellow playwrights often said her achievements far outstripped her fame.
snippet: Ms. Fornés won acclaim and awards for her experimental works. But her fellow playwrights often said her achievements far outstripped her fame.
lead_paragraph: María Irene Fornés, a Cuban-born American playwright whose spare, poetic and emotionally forceful works were hallmarks of experimental theater for four decades, died on Tuesday in Manhattan. She was 88.

headline.main: María Irene Fornés, Writer of Spare, Poetic Plays, Dies at 88
headline.print_headline: María Irene Fornés, 88, Playwright Who, to Her Peers, Was a Genius

abstract: A new therapeutic array of ballpark fragrances at a Bronx nursing home helps older residents recall their youthful trips to Yankee Stadium.
snippet: A new therapeutic array of ballpark fragrances at a Bronx nursing home helps older residents recall their youthful trips to Yankee Stadium.
lead_paragraph: Rochelle Youner, who lives at the Hebrew Home at Riverdale, a nursing home in the Bronx, walked up to a kiosk in a common area of the home’s first floor and pressed a button below a small icon depicting a baseball glove.

abstract: One-third of patients over age 65 die in the hospital after they are put on ventilators. Doctors are beginning to wonder if the procedure should be used so often.
snippet: One-third of patients over age 65 die in the hospital after they are put on ventilators. Doctors are beginning to wonder if the procedure should be used so often.
lead_paragraph: Earlier this year, an ambulance brought a man in his 80s to the emergency room at Brigham and Women’s Hospital in Boston. He had metastatic lung cancer; his family had arranged for hospice care at home.

abstract: Lighting that syncs to your circadian rhythms is making waves in interior design.
snippet: Lighting that syncs to your circadian rhythms is making waves in interior design.
lead_paragraph: The Honeybrains cafe in Manhattan’s NoHo neighborhood serves curry cauliflower bowls, turmeric omega juice shots and mood-boosting supplements all intended to enhance mind and body.

abstract: How one woman discovered excessive and unauthorized trading in a fund meant to support her mother and father in their later years.
snippet: How one woman discovered excessive and unauthorized trading in a fund meant to support her mother and father in their later years.
lead_paragraph: Tracey Dewart faced a daunting task last summer: moving her 84-year-old mother, Aerielle, from her Manhattan apartment to an assisted living facility in Brooklyn. Her mother, who has Alzheimer’s, didn’t want to go, but there was little choice after she was found wandering near her home on the Upper East Side several times.

headline.print_headline: Caught in a Broker’s Churn

abstract: Lauren Slater’s new book chronicles the history of mood-regulating drugs, weaving in her own lifelong struggle to get well and stay well.
snippet: Lauren Slater’s new book chronicles the history of mood-regulating drugs, weaving in her own lifelong struggle to get well and stay well.
lead_paragraph: BLUE DREAMS The Science and the Story of the Drugs That Changed Our Minds By Lauren Slater 400 pp. Little, Brown & Company. $28.

headline.main: A Reckoning With an Imperfect Science in ‘Blue Dreams’
headline.print_headline: Matter Over Mind

abstract: Dr. Blobel, at Rockefeller University, discovered that proteins in any given cell carry signals that guide them to where they can do their beneficial job.
snippet: Dr. Blobel, at Rockefeller University, discovered that proteins in any given cell carry signals that guide them to where they can do their beneficial job.
lead_paragraph: Günter Blobel, a molecular biologist who was awarded the 1999 Nobel Prize in Medicine for discovering that proteins in any living cell have virtual ZIP codes that guide them to where they can help regulate body tissues, organs and chemistry, died on Sunday in Manhattan. He was 81.

abstract: When she’s not throwing molten wax on chandeliers, the sculptor and photographer Petah Coyne is readying the story of the Guerrilla Girls.
snippet: When she’s not throwing molten wax on chandeliers, the sculptor and photographer Petah Coyne is readying the story of the Guerrilla Girls.
lead_paragraph: WEST NEW YORK, N.J. — Two shrouded female figures rise from a sumptuous landscape of dark velvet and wax-dipped silk flowers. One is imperious in posture, the other turns away in stubborn resistance. Their tense standoff seems to charge the roiling swells and eddies of material between them.

abstract: The magazine’s Ethicist columnist on how to handle an seemingly alcoholic client and whether to tell an employer you may be quitting.
snippet: The magazine’s Ethicist columnist on how to handle an seemingly alcoholic client and whether to tell an employer you may be quitting.
lead_paragraph: I work in the architecture field as a designer, and I meet with clients in their homes and throughout the construction process to select materials and review designs. Over a period of months or even years, you become very familiar with these clients. Beyond their likes and dislikes, you learn a lot about them and their lives. It’s usually a very pleasant process; however, a client has presented our firm with an unusual situation.

abstract: In graying Japan, concern that drivers with dementia are causing accidents has prompted the authorities to urge older people to surrender their licenses.
snippet: In graying Japan, concern that drivers with dementia are causing accidents has prompted the authorities to urge older people to surrender their licenses.
lead_paragraph: GOTSU, Japan — Before Atsumu Yoshioka, 81, decided to give up driving, there were signs it might be time.

abstract: The worst flu season in nearly a decade has filled emergency rooms and strained resources at medical centers. Hospitalization and infection rates are among the highest in two decades.
snippet: The worst flu season in nearly a decade has filled emergency rooms and strained resources at medical centers. Hospitalization and infection rates are among the highest in two decades.
lead_paragraph: ALLENTOWN, Pa. — By mid-January, the flu season at Lehigh Valley Hospital-Cedar Crest here in Allentown was bad enough to justify dragging out the “surge tent.”

abstract: In rural Pennsylvania, the family-owned department store Dunham’s caters to those who feel left behind by e-commerce or simply prefer to do their shopping at a slower pace.
snippet: In rural Pennsylvania, the family-owned department store Dunham’s caters to those who feel left behind by e-commerce or simply prefer to do their shopping at a slower pace.
lead_paragraph: The “33 hour” sale at Dunham’s begins the morning after Thanksgiving and lasts through Monday, when the local schools are closed for deer-hunting season.

headline.main: ‘We Don’t Do the Black Friday Madness’
headline.print_headline: Far From the Madding Crowd

abstract: Payroll records for more than 14,000 facilities show that the number of nurses and aides at work dips far below average some days and consistently sinks on weekends.
snippet: Payroll records for more than 14,000 facilities show that the number of nurses and aides at work dips far below average some days and consistently sinks on weekends.
lead_paragraph: ITHACA, N.Y. — Most nursing homes had fewer nurses and caretaking staff than they had reported to the government for years, according to new federal data, bolstering the long-held suspicions of many families that staffing levels were often inadequate.

headline.main: ‘It’s Almost Like a Ghost Town.’ Most Nursing Homes Overstated Staffing for Years
headline.print_headline: Nursing Homes Routinely Mask Low Staff Levels

abstract: A company catering to law enforcement and corrections officers has raised privacy concerns with a product that can locate almost anyone’s cellphone across the United States.
snippet: A company catering to law enforcement and corrections officers has raised privacy concerns with a product that can locate almost anyone’s cellphone across the United States.
lead_paragraph: Thousands of jails and prisons across the United States use a company called Securus Technologies to provide and monitor calls to inmates. But the former sheriff of Mississippi County, Mo., used a lesser-known Securus service to track people’s cellphones, including those of other officers, without court orders, according to charges filed against him in state and federal court.

abstract: Frances H. Arnold of the U.S. received half the prize, while her compatriot George P. Smith and Gregory P. Winter of Britain shared the other half.
snippet: Frances H. Arnold of the U.S. received half the prize, while her compatriot George P. Smith and Gregory P. Winter of Britain shared the other half.
lead_paragraph: Three scientists shared this year’s Nobel Prize in Chemistry for tapping the power of evolutionary biology to design molecules with a range of practical uses.

abstract: Surplus weapons left over from Yugoslavia’s civil war are being sold to Swedish gangs, making crime and immigration hot-button issues.
snippet: Surplus weapons left over from Yugoslavia’s civil war are being sold to Swedish gangs, making crime and immigration hot-button issues.
lead_paragraph: STOCKHOLM — In the Stockholm suburb of Varby Gard, it was not unusual to see the figure of a 63-year-old man pedaling a bicycle home after the end of his shift as an aide for disabled adults, hunched against the icy wind of a Swedish winter.

headline.main: Content for Humans About the Content of Humans

abstract: To the modernist notion of “less is more,” he retorted, “Less is a bore,” arguing for ornament, historical references and even humor in architecture.
snippet: To the modernist notion of “less is more,” he retorted, “Less is a bore,” arguing for ornament, historical references and even humor in architecture.
lead_paragraph: Robert Venturi, the influential American architect and theorist whose buildings and best-selling books helped inspire the movement known as postmodernism, in which historic elements enliven contemporary forms, died on Tuesday at his home in Philadelphia. He was 93.

headline.print_headline: Robert Venturi Dies at 93; Architect’s Take on Modernism: ‘Less Is a Bore’

abstract: We asked who you think was overlooked for a Times obituary. You told us, in droves. Today: grandmothers, who molded nations and families.
snippet: We asked who you think was overlooked for a Times obituary. You told us, in droves. Today: grandmothers, who molded nations and families.
lead_paragraph: When we published the first installment of the Overlooked project two weeks ago, we asked readers to suggest people they felt deserved, but didn’t get, New York Times obituaries.

headline.main: Readers Nominate Their Overlooked Grandmothers for a Times Obituary
headline.print_headline: Overlooked by The Times, but Not by Their Grandchildren

abstract: College-planning surveys give a peek into the opaque and little-regulated market of data-mining of minors.
snippet: College-planning surveys give a peek into the opaque and little-regulated market of data-mining of minors.
lead_paragraph: LOWELL, Mass. — Three thousand high school students from across the United States recently trekked to a university sports arena here to attend an event with an impressive-sounding name: the Congress of Future Science and Technology Leaders. Many of their parents had spent $985 on tuition.
